 a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Arundel","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","(of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>arondel</i> ‘little swallow’ (a diminutive of <i>arond</i> ‘swallow’, from Latin <i>hirundo</i>).","habitational name from a place so named in West Sussex, from Old English <i>hārhūne</i> ‘horehound’ (a wild plant, <i>Marrubium vulgare</i>) + <i>dell</i> ‘valley’. This place is the seat of the dukes of Norfolk. In northern England, folk etymology resulted in variants such as   Arendale  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Arrindell","meanings":["West Indian (Dutch Caribbean and the Dominican Republic): probably an altered form of English   Arundel  ."]},{"name":"Arrendale","meanings":["English: variant of   Arundel  ."]},{"name":"Arendale","meanings":["English: variant of   Arundel   2."]},{"name":"Arendall","meanings":["English: variant of   Arundel  ."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":1,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705187,"age":110,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705188,"age":119,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Maud de Arundel Heiress of Poorstock was born about 1105, in Bridport, Dorset, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Robert de Arundell, Baron of Arundell and Mrs Robert de Arundel. She married Gerbert De Percy in 1127, in Poorstock Liberty, Dorset, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. She died in England."},"et":{"Abt 1105–":"umbes 1105–Surnud","1100–Male":"1100–Surnud","1105–Female":"1105–Surnud","1105–1179":"1105–1179","1118–Female":"1118–Surnud","1125–Female":"1125–Surnud","1075–1150":"1075–1150","–Female":"Surnud","before 1100":"enne 1100","Abt 1105":"umbes 1105","1075":"1075","1150":"1150","1118":"1118","1106":"1106","1127